# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fred-jacklitsch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The **1902 major league baseball season** was contested from April 17 through October 5, 1902.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American League (AL), with the Philadelphia Athletics winning the AL pennant.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant for the second consecutive season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Milwaukee Brewers moved and became the St.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns; the franchise would remain in St.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis through 1953, and in 1954 moved again to become the modern Baltimore Orioles.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This season would be the last of this season's Baltimore Orioles, who would fold following the conclusion of the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues renamed as the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The 1902 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1901 season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 17 with every team playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 19, with a one-off game between the Baltimore Orioles and the Boston Americans, with the rest of the season beginning April 23.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 29, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 5.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] 23 tie games (8 in AL, 15 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Across both leagues, Sammy Strang tied as a leader in runs at 109 (108 with the Chicago White Stockings of the AL and 1 with the Chicago Orphans of the NL).
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds leave League Park (where they played for 18 seasons) and move to the Palace of the Fans, where they would go on to play for ten seasons through 1911.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The **1903 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1903.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and the Boston Americans as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first modern World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Americans defeated the Pirates, five games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the World Series, following the one-off 1900 *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first inter-league series since the 1890 World's Championship Series between the National League and defunct-since-1891 American Association.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 World Series would also mark the first championship series that is still celebrated today, as all previous series are considered pre-modern and these early contests are discussed by MLB and baseball historians separately.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] However, the 1903 arrangement was primarily between the two participating clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues, essentially making this season's World Series a voluntary event.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The defunct Baltimore Orioles were replaced by a new franchise in New York City known as the New York Highlanders; it was the last change to the lineup of AL and NL franchises until 1953.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would not return to Baltimore until the St.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns relocated there as a new Baltimore Orioles in 1954.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Orphans and Cleveland Bronchos were renamed as the Chicago Cubs and Cleveland Naps, respectively.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last season with this format, as the following season would see an increase of games played.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 16 with four teams playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 20, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Athletics and the Boston Americans.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 27, while the American League would see its final day of the season on September 29.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The inaugural World Series took place between October 1 and October 13.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (6 in AL, 9 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Americans defeating the Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1903 World Series in eight games.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Termed the "Battle of Ohio", the Cincinnati Reds and Cleveland Naps played an unofficial best of 11-game exhibition series after the regular season, with Cleveland winning the series six games to three.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the enfranchisement of the New York Highlanders, in place of the folded Baltimore Orioles, playing at Hilltop Park in New York City, New York, where they would play for ten seasons through 1912.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] On August 8, in what is known as the worst disaster in American sports spectating history, Black Saturday, a section of balcony at the Philadelphia Phillies' home at the Baker Bowl collapsed, killing 12 spectators and injuring 232.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies played the last 16 of their 61 home games at the home of the American League crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, Columbia Park from August 20.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The **1904 major league baseball season** was contested from April 14 to October 10, 1904.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans and New York Giants finished atop the standings for the American League and National League, respectively.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason: with still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues, the Giants declined to meet the Americans in the 1904 World Series.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the Americans were the defending World Series from the 1903 season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns and Detroit Tigers played 11 consecutive games against each other in September—the first six in Detroit and the final five in St.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis—the most games played consecutively between two teams in major league history.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings shortened their name to the Chicago White Sox.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The 1904 schedule consisted of 154 games (an increase from 140 from the previous season) for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 140-game, 20-games-each format that had been in place from the 1901 season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American League would see their final day of the regular season on October 9 & 10, respectively.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the New York Highlanders, in a rescheduled game, to play at a ballpark in a different locality.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] 29 tie games (18 in AL, 11 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] With still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues regarding the staging of the World Series, the New York Giants refused to play against the Boston Americans or any other team from what they considered an inferior league.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators leave American League Park (where they played three seasons) and move into a new American League Park, where they would go on to play seven seasons through 1910.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Highlanders play one game at Wiedenmeyer's Park in Newark, New Jersey on Sunday, July 17, as a makeup between them and the Detroit Tigers and to avoid New York City's blue laws.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The **1905 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1905.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended October 8, with the New York Giants and the Philadelphia Athletics as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the second modern World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 5 on October 14.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants defeated the Athletics, four games to one, capturing their first modern championship in franchise history.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Stung by criticism from fans and writers for his team's refusal to play in the previous season's World Series, Giants owner John T.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Brush drafted rules during the offseason to formally establish the World Series as a compulsory event.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Both leagues then adopted the agreement in mid-February 1905.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The 1905 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 16 with all but the Detroit Tigers and Cleveland Naps playing.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 8.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 9 and October 14.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the Detroit Tigers, in a rescheduled game, to play at a ballpark in a different locality.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] 19 tie games (11 in AL, 8 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 14 with the New York Giants defeating the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1905 World Series in five games.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators' American League Park was renamed to National Park.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Due to horse races at main home ballpark, Bennett Park, the Detroit Tigers played two games at Neil Park in Columbus, Ohio, home of the Class A minor league Columbus Senators, on July 23 and 24.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The **1907 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1907.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the fourth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 12.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to none (with one tie), capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1906 season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Beaneaters renamed as the Boston Doves.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The 1907 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11 with all but the Brooklyn Superbas and Boston Doves playing.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 6.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 12.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (18 in AL, 12 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 12 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1907 World Series in five games (one of which being a tie).
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The **1910 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1910.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Chicago Cubs and Philadelphia Athletics as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the seventh modern World Series on October 17 and ended with Game 5 on October 23.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Athletics defeated the Cubs, four games to one, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Pittsburgh Pirates from the 1909 season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The 1910 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] For the first time, Opening Day, which took place on April 14, featured all sixteen teams.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the regular season on October 9, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season was on October 15.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 17 and October 23.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] 26 tie games (19 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 17 and ended on October 23 with the Philadelphia Athletics defeating the Chicago Cubs in the 1910 World Series in five games.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators would play their last games at the original National Park with a doubleheader on October 6 against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The park burned down in March 1911 and the Senators moved into a new National Park for the start of the 1911 season.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox would play their last game at South Side Park on June 27, having played ten seasons there going back to their inaugural 1901 season, and opened White Sox Park on July 1, where they would go on to play for 81 seasons through 1990.
[src:fred-jacklitsch/fred-jacklitsch] Jacklitsch died at his home in Laurelton, Queens on the morning of July 18, 1937.
